Good idea — and yes, local minima in the PMF are the standard structural definition of binding sites. A few
  thoughts on what's worth doing, in increasing order of ambition:

  1. Naive 1D minima (cheap, useful as a first pass)

  On the smoothed 1D PMF you already compute:

  - Find local minima with scipy.signal.find_peaks(-pmf, ...).
  - Filter them with three thresholds you expose as CLI flags:
    - depth (prominence in find_peaks) — e.g. ≥ 0.5 kBT, so noise wiggles in bulk don't get flagged.
    - width — e.g. ≥ 1 Å, to suppress single-bin spikes.
    - z-range — only inside [plow − margin, phigh + margin], to ignore the bulk plateau.
  - Define each site's extent as the surrounding region where PMF(z) ≤ PMF_min + 1 kBT (a common convention; 1 kBT ≈
   kT contour). That gives you a (z_lo, z_hi) interval per site, not just a point.

  Output:
  - Annotate _density_pmf.png with vertical lines + labels (S1, S2, …) at each minimum.
  - Write a _binding_sites.dat with site_id, z_min, depth_kBT, z_lo, z_hi, occupancy.
  - Occupancy = fraction of frames with at least one ion of the species inside [z_lo, z_hi]. Cheap to compute from
  ion_zpos and gives a direct number to compare with structural occupancies.

  This alone is enough for use case (i) — comparing with structurally proposed sites. It's ~50 lines.

  2. 2D / 3D minima (for wider channels)

  The 1D profile collapses lateral structure. For a wide pore the same z-slice can contain several distinct sites at
   different (x, y). So:

  - Run scipy.ndimage.minimum_filter on the 2D PMF (XZ and/or YZ) and pick points where pmf == minimum_filter(pmf,
  size=k) and pmf < threshold.
  - Even better, accumulate a true 3D histogram of (x, y, z) (you already collect all three) and find minima in the
  3D PMF. 1 Å³ bins on a typical box are tractable. Then cluster nearby minima (DBSCAN or just connected-components
  on the PMF ≤ PMF_min + 1 kBT mask) so each connected basin becomes one site.
  - This gives sites as 3D blobs (x_center, y_center, z_center, radius) — directly comparable to structural
  coordinates from a PDB.

  This is the right level of detail to match crystallographic / cryo-EM binding sites in K⁺ channels, AQPs, etc.

  3. State assignment + transitions (the MSM-like part)

  Once sites are defined as spatial regions, you essentially get a discrete-state trajectory for free:

  - For every frame and every ion, assign a state: 0 (bulk_lower), 1..N (sites S1..SN), N+1 (bulk_upper), −1
  (membrane interior, unassigned).
  - From those state sequences, build a count matrix C[i,j] = number of i → j transitions across some lag time τ.
  - Symmetric quantities you can extract immediately without full MSM machinery:
    - Mean residence time per site (mean dwell length before the ion leaves).
    - Site → site transition rates, including which sites talk to which (gives you a connectivity graph of the
  pore).
    - Net flux along the connectivity graph — should reproduce the global up/down currents you already compute,
  which is a great sanity check.
  - For real MSM, hand the discretised trajectories to pyemma or deeptime: implied-timescales test for τ, then build
   MSM.from_dtrajs. You'd get committor probabilities (P(reach upper bulk before lower bulk | in site i)) and mean
  first-passage times between sites — the standard observables for permeation pathways.

  The key design choice is what counts as a state. Two pragmatic options:

  - Core-set / milestoning: ion is "in" site i only when inside PMF ≤ PMF_min + 0.5 kBT; between sites it keeps its
  previous label. This gives clean, well-separated states and avoids spurious transitions from boundary jitter —
  usually the right call for MSMs.
  - Voronoi: ion is always assigned to the nearest site center. Simpler, but inflates transition counts.

  What I'd do first

  1. Implement step (1): 1D minima from the existing smoothed PMF, with depth/width thresholds, plot annotations,
  and an occupancy table. Low effort, directly useful.
  2. Add a 3D PMF + connected-component site finder (step 2) as an opt-in flag — you keep the 1D path for narrow
  channels and only pay the 3D cost when needed.
  3. Once sites exist as regions, write a small assign_states() function that turns ion_xpos/ypos/zpos into integer
  state trajectories and dumps a count matrix. That's the entire foundation for an MSM and can be passed to deeptime
   later without changing the analysis script.

  One caveat worth flagging up front: PMF minima from a single trajectory with a handful of permeation events are
  noisy. The 1D PMF you currently get from the test trajectory has plenty of statistics in bulk but very few samples
   deep inside the membrane, so any "site" found there will have large error bars. Worth either (a) reporting a
  bootstrap uncertainty on the depth, or (b) only trusting sites whose occupancy is non-trivial (say > 5% of
  frames). For real binding-site assignment you usually want either a long equilibrium trajectory or enhanced
  sampling — but as a structural comparison tool, even the noisy version is useful.

  Want me to start with step 1 (1D minima + occupancy + annotated plot + _binding_sites.dat)?




